##Cuba's first new crown confirmed, Brazil's stock market plunges: Is Latin America Ready?

Although Latin America is currently less affected by the epidemic, countries will face a huge crisis if the epidemic spreads, due to the current economic situation and insufficient medical investment.

Cuba is facing sanctions from the United States for the first time to confirm a case of COVID-19 pneumonia. The outbreak has officially entered the Latin American country of 11.34 million people.

Because of shortages of medicines and basic commodities, the Cuban government calls for people to make their own masks to protect themselves against the new coronavirus. In addition, another Latin American country, Guyana, also had its first confirmed case. On the same day, the plunge in Brazil's stock market triggered another circuit-breaker.

According to the Havana Times on March 11, the Cuban Ministry of Health issued a statement that day confirmed that three Italian tourists were diagnosed with the new coronavirus.

Four Italian tourists traveling in the central province of Sancti Spíritus Province were sent to the capital, Havana, Thursday for quarantine tests because of respiratory system symptoms, the statement said.

On the 11th, test results showed that three of the tourists confirmed infection, another tourist results were negative. The tourists arrived at the José Martí International Airport on the 9th and went to the Sancti-Spíritus on the same day.

The Cuban authorities are observing people in close contact with the four, and no one has yet shown symptoms. As of the 11th, the three confirmed patients had not developed serious illness.

In response to the outbreak, Cuba's health ministry this week said it had 3,000 special beds and 100 ICU beds ready. About 30 tourists are being quarantined in Havana, 18 of whom tested negative for the virus.

Health Minister Jose Angel Portal said in an interview earlier this week that the government had set aside money to provide medicine, medical equipment and protective gear needed for treatment.

Among the drugs to be treated is the cuban-made IFN-2b Interferon, which is also listed in the fifth edition of the Chinese COVID-19 for pneumonia.

But Portel acknowledged that Cuba currently does not have enough resources to provide masks to the general public, so guidance is available on how to make them at home.

Previously, Cuban media had already called on people to use cotton, linen and other materials, self-made masks. Local factories in Cuba began producing protective masks for medical facilities.

Founded by the late leader, the Fidel Castro, Cuba's health care system was hailed as one of the major achievements of the Cuban revolution and a model for Latin American health care.

But Cuba's pharmaceutical industry imports up to 85 per cent of its resources. Cuba is currently facing a cash shortage and debt-servicing difficulties as a result of United States sanctions.

Cuba negotiated a debt restructuring through the Paris Club of wealthy nations in 2015, but failed to repay the debts of France, Japan and Spain on time in 2019. Last year, Cuba had to repay about $80m.

Under the terms of the consultations, Cuba would face interest of up to 9 per cent if it failed to comply with the full annual repayment plan. Cuba had promised to repay its overdue debt in May.

To add insult to injury, in February a Cayman Islands Investment Fund filed a lawsuit against the Cuban government alleging that Cuba had failed to pay its $1.4 billion debt on time.

Cuba imports 82 per cent of its goods. Venezuela, a key ally in the long-standing United States sanctions and blockade, has provided Cuba with cheap oil and various types of aid, including money.

As Venezuela's economy collapsed, so did Cuba. When President Donald Trump took office, Bolton, a former national security adviser, referred to Cuba, Venezuela and Nicaragua as the "troika of tyranny. ". The sanctions imposed by the United States on Venezuela are in parallel with those imposed on companies that supply Venezuelan oil to Cuba.

Since 2016, Cuba has suffered from a halt in drug production due to a shortage of cash and a decline in imports due to non-payment of debts.

And in Latin America, Cuba is not the only country in trouble if the new crown disease spreads.

Brazilian voters have long complained that the country's health system is the biggest problem, even more so than corruption and organized crime; Colombian voters see health care as a bigger problem than terrorism.

Latin America spends just $949 a year on health, far less than the $3,973 per head of the Organisation for Economic co-operation and Development (OECD) and worse than even the Middle East and North Africa, according to American quarterly.

Public spending on health in Latin America averages only 3.7 per cent of GDP. Before the outbreak of the new crown, the International Monetary Fund had cut its forecast for Latin America's economic growth this year to 1.6 per cent, according to the IMF  .

To date, there have been about 150 confirmed cases in Latin America, including two deaths.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Photograph: Inter American Commission

Brazil, with a population of more than 200 million, has the highest number of confirmed cases among countries, with a cumulative total of 52 confirmed cases and no deaths. Most of the confirmed cases are in São Paulo.

The first confirmed case in Latin America came from the region's largest economy. In February, a 61-year-old man returned to Sao Paulo from northern Italy, where he celebrated carnival with more than 30 relatives. The man and his relatives were confirmed to be infected.

On March 11, the Sao Paulo Stock Exchange index triggered the circuit breaker mechanism for the second time as oil prices tumbled and the new crown epidemic spread, closing down 7.6 percent from the previous day at 85,171.

The index fell as much as 10.11 percent in the afternoon after World Health Organization Director General Tan Desai declared the outbreak to be a pandemic, triggering a circuit breaker that halted trading for 30 minutes, Xinhua reported.

This is the second time this week that the Brazilian stock market has triggered a circuit breaker. The Sao Paulo Stock Exchange index plunged as much as 10.02 percent Monday morning.

The Brazilian Economy Ministry also released a report that cut its forecast for growth this year to 2.1 percent from 2.4 percent.

Although it is the country with the largest number of confirmed cases in Latin America, Brazil has not yet declared entry restrictions. The Ministry of Health only advises people to avoid close contact and to wash their hands frequently.

El Salvador, Peru and Panama announced on Wednesday that they would close schools across the country; Costa Rica announced that it would cancel all major gatherings, including soccer games; and Bolivia ordered passengers from affected areas to be quarantined for two weeks Chile has called for a quarantine for passengers from Spain and Italy.

Argentina, which has the first death in Latin America, has imposed a two-week quarantine on passengers from China, Italy, France, Germany, Spain, Japan, South Korea and the United States.

The rules could also have an impact on the 2022 World Cup, which has two qualifiers scheduled for Argentina at the end of this month.

To date, 21 cases have been confirmed in Argentina, including one death. The patient was a 64-year-old man who had travelled to France.
